{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504317","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504317"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:14:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2320"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2320"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.06,0.58,0.18,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31518"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17307"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"35"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"11676"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"909"},{"type":"contributions","id":"961"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/31518"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 67-year-old man presents with his wife to the emergency department complaining of a 30 minute history of sudden onset dizziness, nausea and vomiting. His wife notes that his speech has been difficult to understand over this period. He denies weakness or sensation changes throughout his body. He has otherwise been healthy aside from hypertension, for which he takes ramipril.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which of the following examination findings if present would be MOST concerning for a central cause of vertigo?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Positive head impulse testing","Positive Dix-Hallpike manoeuvre","Bidirectional horizontal nystagmus","Unidirectional horizontal nystagmus","Negative test of skew"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EVertigo is a sensation of spinning, dizziness, swaying or tilting. It is a symptom that arises due to asymmetry in the vestibular system due to dysfunction of the labyrinth, vestibular nerve or central structures in the brainstem.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe causes of vertigo range from benign to life threatening. Vertigo can be differentiated into peripheral (affecting the nerve or the labyrinth) or central (affecting the brainstem). Peripheral causes include Meniere disease, labyrinthitis, benign paroxysmal positional vertigo (BPPV) among others. Central causes are potentially life threatening and may represent posterior circulation stroke.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are a number of ways to differentiate peripheral and central causes of vertigo, however clinical assessment, particularly the examination is most helpful in distinguishing. Features seen in central vertigo, and not in peripheral include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENystagmus (bidirectional \u003C/strong\u003Eor vertical)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGait and balance (grossly impaired in central vertigo)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPositive test of skew\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENormal head impulse test\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFeatures that would suggest a peripheral cause include: a positive Dix-Hallpike manoeuvre, a positive head impulse test, horizontal nystagmus that is suppressed by visual fixation and a negative test of skew.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen features of examination are suggestive of a central cause of vertigo, imaging of the brain with MRI is indicated for diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["A vertigo of central origin could have a potential life-threatening cause."],"references":["Chen L, Lee W, Chambers BR, Dewey HM. Diagnostic accuracy of acute vestibular syndrome at the bedside in a stroke unit. J Neurol. 2011;258(5):855-61.","Gold DR, Reich SG. Clinical reasoning: a 55-year-old woman with vertigo. A dizzying conundrum. Neurology. 2012;79(17):e146-52.","Newman-Toker DE, Kerber KA, Hsieh YH, Pula JH, Omron R, Saber Tehrani AS, et al. HINTS outperforms ABCD2 to screen for stroke in acute continuous vertigo and dizziness. Acad Emerg Med. 2013;20(10):986-96."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17307"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2320"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"17307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/17307"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-01-11T16:26:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-10T16:46:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"31518"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"35","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/35"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc43","name":"Otorhinolaryngology","synonyms":["ENT","HEENT"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:40:48+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"ta